<subSubSection id="C3339DA8FF82FFB5AF5BE883FD21FDBB" pageId="40" pageNumber="379" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B96CE23FF82FFB5AF5BE883FF04FF52" blockId="40.[121,225,200,225]" box="[121,225,200,225]" pageId="40" pageNumber="379">
<emphasis id="B95D1231FF82FFB5AF5BE883FF04FF52" box="[121,225,200,225]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="379">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B96CE23FF82FFB5AF5BE8B0FD21FDBB" blockId="40.[121,1089,251,521]" pageId="40" pageNumber="379">
<taxonomicName id="4C29B5A0FF82FFB5AF5BE8B0FE91FEA6" authorityName="Giron &amp; Franz" authorityYear="2010" box="[121,372,251,277]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Apodrosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mammuthus">
<emphasis id="B95D1231FF82FFB5AF5BE8B0FE91FEA6" box="[121,372,251,277]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="379">Apodrosus mammuthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by the combination of its large size (at 6 mm it is the largest species in the genus), a long and escudate body 
<taxonomicName id="4C29B5A0FF82FFB5AC12E955FC50FE8B" box="[816,949,286,312]" form="which" pageId="40" pageNumber="379" rank="form">form which</taxonomicName>
is 2.8-times longer than its greatest width in dorsal view, which is at the anterior third of the elytra, a visible nasal plate, only slightly projected eyes, and a vestiture composed of white iridescent (reddish) scales and with curved, decumbent white setae. This species may be differentiated from the otherwise very similar 
<taxonomicName id="4C29B5A0FF82FFB5AD94E9E2FCACFE70" authorityName="Wolcott" authorityYear="1924" box="[694,841,425,451]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Apodrosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argentatus">
<emphasis id="B95D1231FF82FFB5AD94E9E2FD22FE70" box="[694,711,425,451]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="379">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B95D1231FF82FFB5ADF8E9E1FCACFE70" box="[730,841,426,451]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="379">argentatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its more elongate head, and the aedeagus with a pair of denticulate pads on the endophallus positioned apicad of midpoint, and a thickened apical margin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
